definition.value: Aldehydic parent sugars (polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH(OH)]nC(=O)H, n >= 2) and their intramolecular hemiacetals.
A pyrimidine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside having cytosine as the nucleobase.
Any alpha-amino acid having L-configuration at the alpha-carbon.
An aconitate(3-) that is the conjugate base of trans-aconitic acid.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate having uracil as the nucleobase.
A sinapic acid in which the double bond has trans-configuration.
A streptomycin phosphate having the phosphate group placed at the 3''-position.

A 1,8-naphthyridine derivative that is 1,4-dihydro-1,8-naphthyridine with an ethyl group at the 1 position, a carboxy group at the 3-position, an oxo sustituent at the 4-position, a fluoro substituent at the 5-position and a piperazin-1-yl group at the 7 position. An antibacterial, it is used in the treatment of urinary-tract infections and gonorrhoea.
A tertiary amine oxide resulting from the oxidation of the amino group of trimethylamine.
An alkane-alpha,omega-diamine comprising a propane skeleton with amino substituents at positions 1 and 3.
An optically active form of ornithine having L-configuration.

A primary alcohol is a compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom which has either three hydrogen atoms attached to it or only one other carbon atom and two hydrogen atoms attached to it.
The N-carbamoyl derivative of sarcosine.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of formic acid. Induces severe metabolic acidosis and ocular injury in human subjects.

An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid resulting from the formal oxidation of each of the terminal methyl groups of butane to the corresponding carboxy group. It is an intermediate metabolite in the citric acid cycle.
A polyazaalkane that is tetradecane in which the carbons at positions 1, 5, 10 and 14 are replaced by nitrogens. Spermine has broad actions on cellular metabolism.
A straight-chain, sixteen-carbon, saturated long-chain fatty acid.

A member of the class of chloromethanes that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been replaced by chlorine. A dense, non-flammible colourless liquid at room temperature (b.p. 40degreeC, d = 1.33) which is immiscible with water, it is widely used as a solvent, a paint stripper, and for the removal of caffeine from coffee and tea.
A cephalosporin antibiotic carrying a 3-acetoxymethyl substituent and a 6-oxo-N(6)-L-lysino group at position 7.
A cyclic peptide antibiotic produced by the actinomycete Streptomyces puniceus, used in the treatment of tuberculosis.
An N-acyl-D-glucosamine 6-phosphate that is the  N-acetyl derivative of D-glucosamine 6-phosphate. It is a component of the aminosugar metabolism.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy groups of malonic acid.
An  aminobenzoic acid that is benzoic acid substituted at C-2 by an amine group and at C-3 by a hydroxy group. It is an intermediate in the metabolism of the amino acid tryptophan.
A poly(glycerol phosphate) compound having a D-alanyl-L-alanyl moiety attached to the hydroxy group of the repeating unit.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having palmitoyl as the acyl group.
The 12-dehydro derivative of tetracycline.
A D-alpha-amino acid that is the D-isomer of arginine.
Fructose is a levorotatory monosaccharide and an isomer of glucose.  Although fructose is a hexose (6 carbon sugar), it generally exists as a 5-member hemiketal ring (a furanose).
An alkyl alcohol that is butan-1-ol substituted by a methyl group at position 3.
A cephalosporin having an acetoxy group at the 3-position and a 5-carboxy-5-oxopentanamido group at the 7-position.
A peptide containing ten or more amino acid residues.
A long-chain fatty acid that is a C20, polyunsaturated fatty acid having four (Z)-double bonds at positions 5, 8, 11 and 14.
The oxidised form of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide found in all living cells. In metabolism, NAD(+) is involved in redox reactions, carrying electrons from one reaction to another.
A D-mannosyl-D-glyceric acid where an alpha-D-mannosyl residue is attached at the 2-position.
A cinchona alkaloid that is cinchonidine in which the hydrogen at the 6-position of the quinoline ring is substituted by methoxy.

A deoxyglucose that is D-glucose in which the hydroxy group at position 2 has been replaced by a hydrogen. It is an antimetabolite of glucose with antiviral activity, which acts by inhibiting the glycosylation of glycoproteins and glycolipids. Used as an antiherpes agent.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the hydrate of betaine aldehyde.
A 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose 6-phosphate that has an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
An organic hydroxy compound that consists of benzene bearing a single hydroxy substituent. The parent of the class of phenols.
A delta-amino acid comprising pentanoic acid with an amino substituent at C-5; a methylene homologue of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) that is a weak GABA agonist.
Any 3-hydroxy steroid whose skeleton is closely related to cholestan-3-ol (additional carbon atoms may be present in the side chain).

An amino sulfonic acid that is the 2-amino derivative of ethanesulfonic acid. It is a naturally occurring amino acid derived from  methionine and cysteine metabolism. An abundant component of fish- and meat-based foods, it has been used as an oral supplement in the treatment of disorders such as cystic fibrosis and hypertension.
A galactonolactone derived from D-galactonic acid.
D-Glucopyranose with beta configuration at the anomeric centre.
